if x is the simplest: if True then print "x". There is no logic, we just do it or we donâ€™t depending on whether x is True.
if x and y is the â€˜park and ice cream questionâ€™: thereâ€™s no ice cream without going to the park. So both things have to be True for this to work out happily and print("x and y").
if x or y is the â€˜cereal or toast for breakfastâ€™ question: my daughter is having breakfast either way, so if she answers â€˜Yesâ€™ (True) to either then it doesnâ€™t matter that the other one is False, sheâ€™s still had breakfast, or weâ€™re still printing â€œx or yâ€. And note, if she was really hungry and said yes to both then that would also be breakfast. So if they are both True thatâ€™s also fine.
if x and not y: is the negation of one term. So â€˜if you behave and donâ€™t touch that again then you will get a treatâ€™ is what weâ€™re looking for here. But you can also negate the entire thing: not(x and y) is also valid logic. So this turns a False on if x and y into a True.

